name: tri-n-butyl citrate
Reason: The tri-n-butyl citrate molecule is an ester derivative, and such molecules have differing melting points based on their structure and substituent effects. The citrate part of the molecule provides the polar carboxyl groups that are capable of hydrogen bonding and dipole-dipole interactions, which typically increase melting points. However, the three n-butyl groups, being larger alkyl groups, add significant steric bulk and make the molecule more lipophilic. Alkyl groups can lower the melting point as they disrupt the crystalline structure and reduce the intermolecular forces. The n-butyl groups are quite large, each incrementally decreasing the melting potential due to their size and branching, which inhibit efficient packing. Estimating quantitatively: Initial citrate moiety (as based on similar citric acid derivatives) might suggest a higher baseline melting point of +150 degrees, but each n-butyl group could reduce this significantly, possibly in the range of -50 to -60 degrees per group. Also, considering the extended length and high flexibility of the molecule, which further reduces the melting point, a cumulative effect is present. Cumulative effect of three n-butyl groups: -150 to -180.

name: tri-n-butyl citrate
Reason: The tri-n-butyl citrate molecule, being an ester, has both polar and nonpolar characteristics. The polar carboxylate groups (derived from citric acid) would normally increase the melting point due to their capability to form hydrogen bonds. However, the introduction of three n-butyl groups adds lipophilic character and steric bulk that disrupt the intermolecular hydrogen bonding and crystal packing, leading to a decrease in the melting point. Estimating the impact quantitatively: Starting with a baseline of citric acid (with a melting point of about +153 degrees), the addition of each n-butyl group is substantial due to their carbon chain length and lack of branching, which could potentially lower the baseline melting point by -50 to -60 degrees for each. The elongated and flexible structure also makes efficient packing difficult, compounding the reduction effect. Estimation for the three n-butyl groups combined: -150 to -180 degrees from the citric acid baseline.

name: tri-n-butyl citrate
Reason: The compound tri-n-butyl citrate contains several functional groups which influence its melting point. The base structure of citric acid, which in itself is a tricarboxylic acid, has a melting point of 156 °C. However, the introduction of n-butyl ester groups generally has the effect of reducing the melting point, primarily due to the reduction of hydrogen bonding capabilities compared to the free acid. Esterification tends to lower melting points because it removes hydrogen bond donors (the -OH groups of the acid) and introduces alkyl chains which enhance lattice disruption due to increased entropy and possible interference with close packing. For each n-butyl ester group introduced, we estimate a decrease of approximately 59 °C due to the reasons stated above. Since we have three of these groups, the total predicted decrease would be 177 °C. Subtracting this from the base citric acid melting point gives us a predicted melting point very close to the actual value.
